Third-party components
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

This software depends on the following Apache License 2.0 components, used
(behind opt-in cargo features) for platform-specific GPU hardware video
codec access. Their copyrights and licenses are retained here per Apache-2.0
section 4(d):

  * shiguredo_nvcodec — Rust bindings for the NVIDIA Video Codec SDK
    (NVENC / NVDEC). Copyright Shiguredo Inc. Licensed under Apache-2.0.
    https://github.com/shiguredo/nvcodec-rs
    Used by the `nvidia` feature (crates/codec/src/encode/nvenc.rs).

  * shiguredo_amf — Rust bindings for AMD AMF (Advanced Media Framework).
    Copyright Shiguredo Inc. Licensed under Apache-2.0.
    https://github.com/shiguredo/amf-rs
    Used by the `amd` feature (crates/codec/src/encode/amf.rs).

  * shiguredo_vpl — Rust bindings for Intel oneVPL (Video Processing
    Library). Copyright Shiguredo Inc. Licensed under Apache-2.0.
    https://github.com/shiguredo/vpl-rs
    Used by the `qsv` feature (crates/codec/src/{decode,encode}/qsv.rs).

These wrapper crates load the respective vendor runtime libraries (NVIDIA
CUDA / NVENC, AMD AMF, Intel oneVPL/VA-API) dynamically at runtime via
dlopen; the underlying vendor SDKs are proprietary and are not redistributed
with this software.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

This software also uses a number of additional open-source Rust crates from
the broader ecosystem, distributed under permissive licenses (predominantly
MIT and/or Apache-2.0; some BSD/ISC). A full machine-readable inventory of
the dependency tree and its licenses can be produced with `cargo metadata`
or `cargo about`. Notable ones include: tokio, anyhow, thiserror, tracing,
bytes, clap, mp4, matroska-demuxer, libloading, tempfile (MIT/Apache-2.0);
minimp3 (MIT), lewton (MIT/Apache-2.0), audiopus (ISC, binding to libopus
under the BSD license), rubato (MIT); and, when the `ffmpeg` feature is
enabled, ffmpeg-next (binding to FFmpeg, which is LGPL-2.1+/GPL-2+ — review
its obligations before distributing an `ffmpeg`-enabled build).
